[1
Date: Sun 17 Mar 2002
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Agencia EFE (via COMTEX), Sat 16 Mar 2002 [edited

Chile declares dengue fever health alert on Easter Island
---------------------------------------------------------
SANTIAGO: The Chilean government declared a health alert on Easter Island
(3700 km/2229 miles) west of the continent, following the confirmation of a
case of dengue fever, the Health Ministry announced on Sat 16 Mar 2002. "We
have declared a health alert on Easter Island following the appearance of
its first case of contagious dengue," assistant health minister Gonzalo
Navarrete said after traveling to the Chilean territory with a group of
specialists to investigate a possible outbreak of the disease on the
island. The Public Health Institute confirmed on Fri 15 Mar 2002 that a 21
year old woman contracted the disease a few days ago, but has now been
released from the hospital. The Health Ministry said it was not certain if
the woman had contracted dengue fever during her 3 month stay on Easter
Island or upon arrival in Santiago.
Nevertheless, the director of the hospital on Easter Island, Dr Cristian
Perez, confirmed that the facility had treated at least 6 patients with
symptoms of dengue fever. "We have one suspicious case to confirm, but none
of the patients are in serious condition," Perez told the state-run
television station. The _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito that transmits dengue may
have come to the island with the scores of Tahitian tourists who visited in
January, Perez added. "We will investigate any future cases of dengue, and
it is necessary for the residents of Easter Island to remain calm,"
Navarrete insisted.
