[2
Date Mon 18 Mar 2002
From: "Pablo Nart" <p.nart@virgin.net>
Source: Sun Sentinel, Sat 16 March 2002 [edited

Easter Island: first case of dengue fever
-----------------------------------------
Easter Island, one of the world's most isolated populated places, became
the site on Fri 15 Mar 2002 of Chile's first recent case of dengue fever,
which has reached epidemic proportions in Brazil this year and plagues 100
countries worldwide.
Health officials confirmed one case of the illness on the remote Pacific
island, known for its giant stone monoliths, and said 2 other people were
thought to have it but had not been fully diagnosed [The preceding report
does not confirm unequivocally that the confirmed case contracted infection
on Easter Island. - Mod.CP.
The disease is transmitted by [the mosquito _Aedes aegypti_ and was
probably carried to the remote South Pacific island by a tourist who was
then bitten by a mosquito that spread the virus to local residents,
officials said. There have been no cases reported on mainland Chile, which
has jurisdiction over Easter Island.
--
Pablo Nart
<p.nart@virgin.net>
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[If confirmed by laboratory diagnosis, these suspected case of dengue fever
may mark the first appearance of the disease on Easter Island. These two
reports conflict as to the possible source of the virus, that is, whether
introduced by an infected tourist or by an infected mosquito. As a
precaution it would be prudent at this stage for the local authorities to
investigate the mosquito population for presence of the potential vector.
ProMED-mail would welcome further information on the disease status of
Easter Island as it becomes known. - Mod.CP
